# TypeScript Coding Guidelines

<!-- Edit this file directly. Committed to git and shared with the team. -->

## Style
- Use TypeScript strict mode (`"strict": true` in tsconfig)
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow explicitly
- Prefer `const` over `let`, never `var`

## Naming
- Variables/functions: camelCase
- Classes/interfaces/types: PascalCase
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE or camelCase (consistent within module)
- Files: kebab-case

## Types
- Prefer interfaces over type aliases for objects
- Use discriminated unions for state machines
- Export types separately from implementations
- No implicit `any` — if you can't type it, use `unknown`

## Functions
- Prefer arrow functions for callbacks
- Named functions for top-level declarations
- Avoid callback hell — use async/await

## Async
- Always `async/await` over raw `.then()` chains
- Handle errors with try/catch, not `.catch()` swallowing
- Never `async () => { something(); }` without awaiting the promise

## Imports
- Named imports preferred over default imports
- Absolute imports with path aliases (configure in tsconfig)
- No circular dependencies

## Error handling
- Use typed error classes: `class AppError extends Error { code: string }`
- Don't swallow errors: `catch (e) { console.error(e); throw e; }`
- Return `Result<T, E>` patterns for expected failure paths

## Testing (Jest/Vitest)
- Test files: `*.test.ts` co-located with source, or in `__tests__/`
- Mock external services with jest.mock() or vi.mock()
- Use `describe` blocks to group related tests
- Test names: "should [behaviour] when [condition]"

## React (if used)
- Functional components with hooks only
- Props typed with interfaces
- No inline function definitions in JSX (extract to named functions)
- Custom hooks for stateful logic
